[{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"# The box model in CSS\n\nCSS uses the box model. That means, every element in HTML is treated as a box. Every box has some content, for example text, a padding, which is the distance from the content to the end of the box, the border, which is around the box, and the margin, which is the distance of the element to other elements.\n\nTo visualize that, you can run the HTML and CSS code below:"},{"kind":2,"language":"html","value":"<div>\n  <p>Hello World</p>\n</div>"},{"kind":2,"language":"css","value":"div {\n  display: inline-block;\n  background-color: #e4e4e4;\n}\n\np {\n  border: 1px solid #000000;\n  padding: 2em;\n  margin: 1em;\n  background-color: #666666;\n}"},{"kind":1,"language":"markdown","value":"As you can see, the p-element has an padding of `2em` inside the element, which is the double of the margin to the parent-element."}]